WEBVTT

00:06.965 --> 00:09.885
[♪ creepy rhythmic pulsing]

00:09.968 --> 00:12.971
[♪ eerie music playing]

00:18.894 --> 00:21.146
[♪ horror sting]

00:21.230 --> 00:24.233
♪♪

00:27.361 --> 00:29.112
[speaker 1]
So, very young...

00:29.196 --> 00:32.573
[branches rustling]

00:32.658 --> 00:35.077
...I got obsessed with horror.

00:35.160 --> 00:37.788
[chair squeaking]

00:37.871 --> 00:39.039
[heavy breathing]

00:39.122 --> 00:42.000
I just think it would be fun
to survive a horror movie.

00:42.084 --> 00:44.044
♪♪

00:47.673 --> 00:50.259
[buzzing]

00:50.342 --> 00:53.345
-[light clicks]
-[indistinct murmuring]

00:54.888 --> 00:56.181
[slice]

00:56.265 --> 00:58.725
But you make it to the end...

00:58.809 --> 00:59.893
[screaming]

00:59.977 --> 01:01.603
♪♪

01:01.687 --> 01:03.897
...and the credits roll,
and everyone's fine.

01:03.981 --> 01:05.482
[screaming]

01:05.566 --> 01:08.110
That's just always been, like,
super appealing to me.

01:08.819 --> 01:12.406
I think I googled,
"Survive your own scary movie,"

01:13.198 --> 01:16.493
which is where
the beginning of this started.

01:16.577 --> 01:19.580
♪♪

01:20.789 --> 01:23.750
[speaker 2]
But, every horror movie...

01:23.834 --> 01:25.669
[♪ horror music playing]

01:25.752 --> 01:27.588
[screaming]

01:27.671 --> 01:30.007
-[static hissing]
-...has a monster.

01:32.259 --> 01:34.178
[♪ music fades out]

01:34.261 --> 01:35.679
[screaming]

01:35.762 --> 01:37.639
Hey, everybody. It's Russ.

01:37.723 --> 01:38.849
[screaming]

01:38.932 --> 01:41.059
This is Immersive Horror,

01:41.143 --> 01:44.062
where you become the star of the show.

01:44.146 --> 01:46.106
[screaming] No!

01:46.190 --> 01:48.150
[speaker 2]
No, Russ. Please...

01:48.233 --> 01:50.903
[Russ McKamey]
[panting] Stay with me, honey.

01:50.986 --> 01:53.322
-[speaker 2 pleading]
-[Russ] Hold your breath.

01:53.405 --> 01:56.992
On the count of three, hold your breath.
One. Two.

01:57.075 --> 02:00.078
-[water pouring]
-[echoing hyperventilating]

02:01.705 --> 02:04.333
-[speaker 2] Please--
-[silence]

02:04.416 --> 02:07.002
[speaker 3]
An immersive horror experience is...

02:07.085 --> 02:08.587
[overlapping screaming]

02:08.670 --> 02:12.424
...you are basically putting yourself
inside of a horror movie.

02:12.508 --> 02:14.051
[indistinct screaming]

02:14.134 --> 02:16.762
My legs hurt, and my arms hurt,
a-and my hands are freezing.

02:16.845 --> 02:20.224
And I can't feel them 'cause there's still
shocks running through my hands.

02:20.307 --> 02:21.767
[interviewer]
You had a good time, though?

02:21.850 --> 02:22.935
Yes! I had a great time.

02:23.602 --> 02:27.397
-[people screaming]
-[♪ horror music playing]

02:27.481 --> 02:30.234
I don't know too many people
outside of my small little group

02:30.317 --> 02:31.693
that know about this stuff.

02:31.777 --> 02:35.197
[♪ creepy music playing]

02:35.280 --> 02:36.823
It is relatively underground,

02:36.907 --> 02:39.284
and right now, we have
the worst salesman for it

02:39.368 --> 02:41.954
in the history of bad salesmen.
That's Russ McKamey.

02:42.037 --> 02:43.830
♪♪

02:43.914 --> 02:47.668
I am the owner and creator
of McKamey Manor,

02:47.751 --> 02:51.922
the world's most extreme haunted house.

02:52.005 --> 02:54.341
-[♪ creepy music playing]
-[inaudible screaming]

02:54.424 --> 02:57.511
Russ has positioned himself to be

02:57.594 --> 02:59.847
-the great danger.
-[liquid splashes]

02:59.930 --> 03:03.141
You're in boot camp,
you are in North Korea,

03:03.225 --> 03:05.394
you are in Stalinist Russia,

03:05.477 --> 03:08.063
and you're gonna see
if you can make it out or not.

03:08.146 --> 03:10.190
-[person panting]
-[Russ] We're showmen.

03:10.274 --> 03:14.152
I am the P.T. Barnum of the haunt world.

03:14.236 --> 03:15.779
Look at her. Look at her.

03:15.863 --> 03:19.449
I spent hours trying to convince her
not to show up here.

03:19.533 --> 03:20.909
But she wouldn't listen to me.

03:20.993 --> 03:22.828
The show's never over with Russ.

03:22.911 --> 03:24.288
-[gasping]
-[splashing]

03:24.371 --> 03:26.874
Please stop, Russ. Please, please.

03:28.000 --> 03:29.751
Russ has crossed the Rubicon.

03:29.835 --> 03:32.421
There's no goin' back.

03:32.504 --> 03:35.257
I'm leaving McKamey Manor, thank God.

03:35.340 --> 03:37.217
Do. Not. Come. Here.

03:38.760 --> 03:40.971
[projector clicking, whirring]

03:41.054 --> 03:43.348
[♪ eerie music playing]

03:43.432 --> 03:45.058
[♪ eerie crescendo]

03:47.186 --> 03:50.189
[wind blowing]

03:50.272 --> 03:53.233
[birds chirping]

03:56.236 --> 03:59.239
[Russ] McKamey Manor
has a history of, um, cities and towns...

03:59.323 --> 04:02.117
-[♪ dramatic sting]
-...not wanting us in their location.

04:02.201 --> 04:05.495
You know, we were kicked out of Illinois.
We were gonna move out there.

04:05.579 --> 04:08.540
Um, the city saw the movies
after we were there,

04:08.624 --> 04:10.584
basically, and freaked out.

04:10.667 --> 04:13.170
And they were, you know,
they just went crazy,

04:13.253 --> 04:16.173
you know, praying in front of the building
to keep us away,

04:16.256 --> 04:20.469
shooting out the windows, slashing tires.
I mean, they really did not want us there.

04:20.552 --> 04:23.722
[bees buzzing loudly]

04:23.805 --> 04:26.808
[♪ pulsating creepy music playing]

04:29.520 --> 04:32.022
[jet engine whining]

04:32.105 --> 04:33.148
[muffled thud]

04:34.149 --> 04:35.150
[♪ dramatic sting]

04:35.984 --> 04:37.986
-[people clapping]
-[♪ guitar playing]

04:38.070 --> 04:41.949
[emcee] Hey, everybody, welcome to the
Captain's pizza party! It's time to party!

04:42.032 --> 04:45.536
♪ I really, really, really, really,
really, really, really like girls ♪

04:45.619 --> 04:46.787
♪♪

04:46.870 --> 04:50.749
♪ Yeah, I really, really, really, really,
really, really, really like girls ♪

04:50.832 --> 04:53.919
[interviewer] You are from the military,
you were in the Navy.

04:54.002 --> 04:57.589
[Russ] Oh, absolutely. Yeah,
I've-I was in the military for 23 years.

04:57.673 --> 05:01.134
Even on a ship, I had a haunt going on.

05:01.218 --> 05:03.178
[♪ foreboding music building]

05:03.262 --> 05:05.806
[news anchor]
Russ McKamey created a house of horror

05:05.889 --> 05:08.976
that would rival anything
at a carnival or theme park.

05:09.059 --> 05:11.562
-Nine rooms, animated ghoulish figures,
-[cackling]

05:11.645 --> 05:13.313
you wonder what he spent on it.

05:13.397 --> 05:15.274
This year, about $30,000.

05:15.357 --> 05:17.234
-[cackling]
-[♪ scary music playing]

05:17.317 --> 05:19.987
It took me six months to do
what I did in there so far,

05:20.070 --> 05:21.446
so, and we just ran outta time.

05:21.530 --> 05:24.241
[news anchor] A Navy veteran
who now works with the VFW,

05:24.324 --> 05:27.202
he's just always loved Halloween, he says.

05:27.286 --> 05:29.288
[♪ foreboding music playing]

05:29.371 --> 05:34.042
[Kris] When we first met,
I started doing video work for him.

05:34.960 --> 05:36.670
Russ was my friend.

05:36.753 --> 05:40.048
I thought that me and Russ
were-were best friends.

05:40.132 --> 05:42.342
[♪ curious music playing]

05:42.426 --> 05:45.929
When the manor started originally,
it was an awesome thing.

05:47.014 --> 05:51.435
It was kids working it,
jumping out, scaring you.

05:51.518 --> 05:54.938
You know, there was a line
to get in on Halloween.

05:55.022 --> 05:56.940
-[guests chattering]
-It was a cool thing.

05:57.024 --> 05:58.942
♪♪

05:59.026 --> 06:02.946
That was when the news
on what we were doing got big.

06:03.030 --> 06:06.700
This is considered the scariest
haunted house in America.

06:06.783 --> 06:09.870
-[eerie cackling]
-[Kris] We were on Good Morning America,

06:09.953 --> 06:13.040
every news station,
everybody was doin' a story on us.

06:13.123 --> 06:15.918
[narrator]
McKamey Manor is completely interactive.

06:16.001 --> 06:18.962
-A two-hour visit to hell on Earth.
-[screams]

06:19.046 --> 06:21.924
And then every year,
he had to one up it.

06:22.466 --> 06:25.052
[screaming, shouting]

06:25.135 --> 06:28.555
Had to get a little more intense.
A little more intense to the point,

06:28.639 --> 06:31.850
though, finally,
they got rid of the kids.

06:31.934 --> 06:34.603
-[screaming]
-[Russ] Here they come! They're coming!

06:34.686 --> 06:37.314
[chainsaw roaring]

06:37.898 --> 06:40.734
McKamey Manor promises
an extreme experience

06:40.817 --> 06:42.277
that can last up to 10 hours,

06:42.361 --> 06:45.072
requires participants to be
medically cleared by a doctor

06:45.155 --> 06:48.033
and sign a 40-page waiver.

06:48.116 --> 06:50.536
This place has been
known to break the minds...

06:50.619 --> 06:52.955
It was invented by
this crazy gentleman...

06:53.038 --> 06:56.750
Russ McKamey videotapes
every single second...

06:56.834 --> 07:01.255
...inducing is a form of
psychological torture, but for fun.

07:01.338 --> 07:04.967
[voices overlapping]

07:05.050 --> 07:08.762
[news anchor] They say it amounts
to a torture chamber. Yikes.

07:09.805 --> 07:12.307
-[static hissing]
-[Kris] The phones would not stop.

07:15.769 --> 07:17.396
His phone would constantly ring,

07:17.479 --> 07:21.108
my phone would constantly ring,
with people trying to get in.

07:21.191 --> 07:23.527
It was insane

07:23.610 --> 07:26.864
how quickly and how big it got.

07:26.947 --> 07:29.950
[♪ unsettling music playing]

07:31.326 --> 07:32.953
And that's when it got violent.

07:33.036 --> 07:35.289
-[person wailing]
-[Russ] Don't fuckin' move.

07:35.372 --> 07:36.540
[panting]

07:36.623 --> 07:38.542
[muffled yelling]

07:38.625 --> 07:40.794
-Stop resisting!
-[slam]

07:41.253 --> 07:43.255
I probably wouldn't do the haunt

07:44.214 --> 07:46.884
-if I wasn't able to film it.
-[person yells]

07:47.509 --> 07:50.012
-That's nice.
-[person whimpers]

07:50.095 --> 07:51.305
[crying]

07:51.388 --> 07:54.391
Because I want the world
to see what I'm doing.

07:56.727 --> 07:57.728
[inaudible]

07:57.811 --> 08:00.814
[static, bars & tone]

08:04.067 --> 08:08.030
[breeze blowing]

08:19.291 --> 08:21.460
I am here because I want everyone

08:21.543 --> 08:23.504
to know the truth on Russ.

08:24.796 --> 08:25.797
[clicking]

08:27.466 --> 08:29.259
[inaudible]

08:29.343 --> 08:32.971
I don't feel like I'm,
like, mentally weak,

08:33.055 --> 08:36.099
but it messed me up.

08:36.642 --> 08:39.603
I'm over five years past it...

08:40.145 --> 08:41.146
[clicking]

08:41.230 --> 08:43.106
...and I'm just now coming to terms

08:43.190 --> 08:45.150
with how fucked up it was.

08:45.234 --> 08:46.985
[inaudible]

08:47.069 --> 08:50.697
[speaker 4] The dude lives in the dark.
The world needs to see

08:50.781 --> 08:53.700
what this man has done to people.

08:53.867 --> 08:54.868
[clicking]

08:56.453 --> 08:59.498
If someone asked me my story,
I would tell it to 'em.

08:59.581 --> 09:02.417
There's actually a lesson
to be learned from Russ.

09:03.460 --> 09:06.505
[♪ eerie crescendo]

09:10.509 --> 09:12.219
[TV static buzzing]

09:16.306 --> 09:17.516
[static hissing]

09:23.564 --> 09:26.567
[♪ eerie music playing]

09:30.195 --> 09:34.241
[W.P. West] I am a producer and creator
of immersive horror.

09:35.576 --> 09:37.327
♪♪

09:37.411 --> 09:40.330
I'm putting them through what
I would perceive as horrific.

09:40.414 --> 09:42.332
♪♪

09:42.416 --> 09:46.295
I'm putting them through a scenario
that I'm terrified of.

09:47.254 --> 09:51.216
I love traditional Halloween.
Like, I love old school haunted houses.

09:52.134 --> 09:53.844
An immersive horror experience

09:53.927 --> 09:57.556
is definitely evolved
out of a haunted house,

09:58.765 --> 10:00.851
-but...
-[♪ horror sting]

10:00.934 --> 10:03.520
...you can't compare
these things together.

10:03.604 --> 10:06.815
If you wanna put 'em in a hierarchy,
you know, you have boo haunts up here.

10:06.899 --> 10:09.568
[kids chattering]

10:09.651 --> 10:11.945
[♪ dramatic music playing]

10:12.029 --> 10:15.782
The normal boo haunted house,
they pop out of a hole in the window,

10:15.866 --> 10:18.744
-they scare you around a corner.
-[kids scream]

10:18.827 --> 10:21.288
[Brandon]
Those are just walkabout haunted houses

10:21.371 --> 10:22.623
that everybody can go to.

10:22.706 --> 10:24.958
[inaudible]

10:25.709 --> 10:26.710
[screams]

10:26.793 --> 10:29.796
[♪ creepy music playing]

10:31.715 --> 10:32.799
[screams]

10:32.883 --> 10:35.177
Followed by more extreme haunts...

10:35.260 --> 10:37.346
[people screaming]

10:37.429 --> 10:40.390
...but without necessarily
actors touching you.

10:40.474 --> 10:44.436
[screaming]

10:45.562 --> 10:47.814
As you kind of get into
the more immersive experience,

10:47.898 --> 10:50.817
-they can separate you from your friends.
-[screams]

10:50.901 --> 10:53.904
They can tie you up,
but it's nothing super extreme.

10:53.987 --> 10:55.614
[cuffs clicking]

10:55.697 --> 10:58.033
At the very bottom is...

10:58.116 --> 11:01.662
-[screaming]
-...immersive, extreme type experiences,

11:01.745 --> 11:04.414
where it is full contact.

11:04.498 --> 11:06.708
There's no topic that's off the table.

11:06.792 --> 11:08.293
-[thud]
-[lights click]

11:09.419 --> 11:12.047
[W.P.]
They're longer, they're more intense,

11:12.130 --> 11:14.299
they're more narrative-driven,

11:14.383 --> 11:17.177
more task-driven, and personal.

11:17.261 --> 11:18.762
[♪ music building]

11:19.972 --> 11:21.473
[♪ dramatic sting]

11:24.726 --> 11:27.771
Some of these ultra personal experiences

11:27.855 --> 11:31.525
are made to make you face

11:31.608 --> 11:33.735
all the things that you don't wanna face.

11:33.819 --> 11:35.737
[panting]

11:35.821 --> 11:37.948
[haunter] Hands and knees,
Hands and knees!

11:38.031 --> 11:40.951
[♪ dramatic music playing]

11:41.034 --> 11:44.580
[Brandon] And they go about it
in extremely creative ways.

11:45.372 --> 11:46.790
[muffled]
Fuck!

11:47.958 --> 11:49.126
[snapping]

11:49.209 --> 11:52.129
[breathing heavily]

11:52.212 --> 11:55.299
They put you in situations that you
didn't realize you were even scared of.

11:55.382 --> 11:57.593
♪♪

11:58.927 --> 12:02.431
[incoherent shouting]

12:05.934 --> 12:09.104
People just enjoy the rush of it
'cause it is a thrill.

12:09.188 --> 12:10.898
♪♪

12:10.981 --> 12:13.817
The point is how much
can you take, right?

12:13.901 --> 12:17.154
How much physical and mental abuse

12:17.237 --> 12:19.823
can you put up with
before you just cut out?

12:21.408 --> 12:24.161
But, you can take away
consent at any time,

12:24.244 --> 12:26.872
and a good extreme haunt owner knows that.

12:34.588 --> 12:36.673
You constantly have to
ask the participant,

12:36.757 --> 12:38.425
"Do you still consent?
Do you still consent?"

12:38.509 --> 12:41.929
Even if it's seven hours,
they're going to make sure that I'm safe.

12:42.012 --> 12:44.348
[W.P.]
But it isn't just the torturing people.

12:44.431 --> 12:46.517
There is subtext to the show.

12:46.600 --> 12:49.186
There's subtext to the things
that I'm talking about.

12:49.269 --> 12:52.814
[♪ horror music playing]

12:54.233 --> 12:56.735
But, that isn't always the case.

12:58.153 --> 13:00.656
There's one person

13:00.739 --> 13:03.492
basically running a torture chamber.

13:03.575 --> 13:04.826
♪♪

13:04.910 --> 13:06.537
[panting]

13:06.620 --> 13:09.248
[Russ] [echoing] You made a big mistake.
Come on.

13:09.331 --> 13:12.876
Russ was, like, a celebrity. You know,

13:12.960 --> 13:16.380
every YouTube video at the time,
every Facebook link

13:16.463 --> 13:19.424
was Russ' face, mentioning this haunt.

13:19.508 --> 13:22.094
[laughs] We're here waiting for you.

13:22.177 --> 13:24.388
Russ McKamey's a divisive figure.

13:24.471 --> 13:26.682
[Russ]
Just get him in here! Get him in here!

13:26.765 --> 13:28.141
He uses his divisiveness

13:28.225 --> 13:31.687
to get your attention,
to grow in attention.

13:31.770 --> 13:32.980
[Russ]
You understand what I'm telling you?

13:33.063 --> 13:34.064
[indistinct shouting]

13:34.147 --> 13:36.525
[Russ] Yes what? Tell me what
I just told you, Christina.

13:36.608 --> 13:39.027
He started to put little bits
of information out there

13:39.111 --> 13:41.738
to make himself more infamous, I guess.

13:41.822 --> 13:44.074
[Russ]
You look scared Steve.

13:44.157 --> 13:46.326
-I'm terrified, sir.
-[Russ] Yeah, you need to be.

13:46.410 --> 13:50.163
[Brandon] It billed itself as the most
extreme haunted house in the world.

13:50.247 --> 13:51.915
They do all kinds of crazy stuff to you.

13:51.999 --> 13:53.375
I don't like you here.

13:53.458 --> 13:56.795
I am gonna make sure you have
the worst day of your entire life.

13:56.879 --> 14:00.257
They drugged you,
that they pulled your teeth,

14:00.340 --> 14:03.218
that if you threw up,
they make you eat your throw-up.

14:03.302 --> 14:05.304
And I was like, "How is this possible?

14:05.387 --> 14:07.139
But, man, this is fascinating."

14:07.222 --> 14:10.225
[muffled]
[screams] Let me out!

14:10.309 --> 14:13.478
Let me out! Let me out!

14:13.562 --> 14:15.230
[♪ dramatic crescendo]

14:15.314 --> 14:18.984
[Russ] We only do one
or two shows a week.

14:19.067 --> 14:21.320
-The list is long.
-[muffled screaming]

14:21.403 --> 14:25.157
[Brandon] One of those things
that Russ liked to say was

14:25.240 --> 14:28.744
he had this 27,000 person waitlist.

14:28.827 --> 14:31.079
-[haunter 1] You won the lottery.
-[haunter 2] Out of 20,000.

14:31.163 --> 14:33.540
-[Russ] 27,000.
-[haunter 2] 27,000!

14:33.624 --> 14:36.084
He's so big with this huge waitlist.

14:36.168 --> 14:39.087
[Russ]
I'm offering you 20 grand,

14:39.171 --> 14:43.091
and you know we're probably
not gonna kill ya, so...

14:43.175 --> 14:44.718
There was a $20,000 money prize.

14:44.801 --> 14:47.971
Oh yeah, well, the 20 grand,
that's a big part of it.

14:48.055 --> 14:51.808
Well, here I am.
Today's the day for my McKamey Manor tour.

14:51.892 --> 14:55.771
[Brandon] Some people see that 20 grand,
and they're enticed by that money.

14:55.854 --> 14:57.356
♪♪

14:57.439 --> 15:00.859
[gasps] Everyone on the internet
told me I could do it,

15:00.943 --> 15:04.321
they wanted me to, and I didn't listen.

15:04.404 --> 15:06.657
Do not come here.

15:06.740 --> 15:09.034
[sobs]

15:09.117 --> 15:11.245
♪♪

15:11.328 --> 15:15.874
[Russ] Price of admission
for this eight-hour-plus adventure?

15:15.958 --> 15:19.920
Four cans of dog food
or a bag of dog food.

15:20.003 --> 15:22.506
[Gabi]
He's not making money.

15:22.589 --> 15:26.510
I think most of the money that went into
the haunt was from his previous wife.

15:27.761 --> 15:30.639
But I think it is just to keep himself,
keep himself clean.

15:30.722 --> 15:31.974
♪♪

15:32.057 --> 15:34.434
Haunted houses, like,
this is not a money thing.

15:34.518 --> 15:36.144
You gotta do this for the art,

15:36.228 --> 15:39.690
-or 'cause you're a sociopath.
-[Russ inaudible]

15:39.773 --> 15:41.775
You wanna run a torture chamber.

15:44.152 --> 15:48.240
[Russ] We're known for no quitting
and no safe-wording.

15:48.323 --> 15:49.366
[person panting]

15:49.449 --> 15:53.120
I make it simple 'cause I'm a simple guy,
and I can't have too many rules,

15:53.203 --> 15:56.540
otherwise I'll get confused.
So, either you actually complete the tour,

15:56.623 --> 15:58.876
-which is not going to happen...
-[person panting]

15:58.959 --> 16:03.255
...or you mentally or physically
are at such a breaking point

16:03.338 --> 16:06.049
that it's now not safe
for you to continue,

16:06.133 --> 16:07.843
and I need to take you out.

16:07.926 --> 16:10.929
[♪ scary music playing]

16:12.723 --> 16:18.020
Russ doesn't want you to quit
until you are a pile of bones and flesh.

16:18.103 --> 16:20.355
And then, you're not probably done either.

16:20.439 --> 16:22.232
[static hissing]

16:22.316 --> 16:23.376
[♪ dramatic crescendo]

16:23.525 --> 16:26.528
[insects chirping]

16:33.619 --> 16:36.038
[Brandon] All that bad stuff,
it's selling point.

16:36.830 --> 16:39.541
It's not a reason not to go.
It's a reason to go.

16:39.625 --> 16:40.876
How bad can it be?

16:40.959 --> 16:43.003
[♪ tense music playing]

16:46.757 --> 16:49.885
That's my number one rule
before I go to any extreme haunt.

16:51.845 --> 16:54.848
If a felony's not gonna be taking place,
I don't wanna go.

16:57.893 --> 16:59.520
I love the adrenaline.

17:00.395 --> 17:01.396
[gunshot]

17:02.648 --> 17:05.484
There was no second thought,
there was no nothing. I had to do it.

17:08.445 --> 17:12.616
I had just moved to Los Angeles.
I was, like, trying to be an actress.

17:12.699 --> 17:14.868
I had a group of friends
that were creative,

17:14.952 --> 17:18.705
so we would just do fun little
short films that were scary.

17:18.789 --> 17:20.582
[screaming]

17:20.666 --> 17:22.543
And I wanted something more extreme.

17:22.626 --> 17:25.546
And it was like
a full send point in my life,

17:25.629 --> 17:27.631
where I just didn't think about anything.

17:27.714 --> 17:29.758
I was like, "Okay, like,
you only live once.

17:29.842 --> 17:32.386
Like, why not just try to, like,
get into this haunted house?"

17:32.469 --> 17:33.971
♪♪

17:34.596 --> 17:36.890
[Melissa]
My day-to-day activities,

17:36.974 --> 17:40.102
my normal routine gets dull,

17:40.185 --> 17:42.187
and I wanted to branch out.

17:43.021 --> 17:44.314
And I'm not gonna lie.

17:44.398 --> 17:48.110
I honestly thought that
this was gonna help

17:48.193 --> 17:51.738
get me a little bit of fame.
And I wanted a video of me up on YouTube.

17:51.822 --> 17:53.824
♪♪

17:57.119 --> 18:00.664
And the more people that
I talked to about this that said,

18:00.747 --> 18:03.000
"No, don't do it, don't do it,
don't do it,"

18:04.585 --> 18:06.461
the more it motivated me.

18:08.755 --> 18:12.009
My first conversations with Russ
involved going to his website,

18:12.092 --> 18:15.053
finding out what his email address was,
and I just sent him an email.

18:15.137 --> 18:18.599
And I contacted the admins
about doing a tour.

18:18.682 --> 18:22.519
"I wanna be an actress. I love horror.
Um, I'm trying to start a YouTube channel.

18:22.603 --> 18:24.396
Like, I would love to do this haunt."

18:24.479 --> 18:27.983
Not even two days later,
I actually got the email back from him.

18:28.066 --> 18:30.110
[♪ dramatic music playing]

18:30.194 --> 18:33.155
"Hey, Gabi, are you available tomorrow?

18:33.238 --> 18:35.866
I have, like, a spot opening up.
Someone bailed."

18:35.949 --> 18:39.328
We kind of bonded because
we were both in the service.

18:39.411 --> 18:43.332
He says, "This is your only opportunity
to get in. I got 20,000 people waiting,

18:43.415 --> 18:45.542
I'm bumping you
to the front of the line."

18:45.626 --> 18:48.086
People get so obsessed,
and Russ is feeding their ears,

18:48.170 --> 18:51.048
and they're like,
"This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,

18:51.131 --> 18:53.175
because I'll never get this chance again."

18:53.258 --> 18:56.762
Then, I had to do this little video
that Russ asked me to do,

18:56.845 --> 19:00.724
live on this private Facebook group.

19:00.807 --> 19:04.561
I had a friend hanging me
by my ankles upside down,

19:04.645 --> 19:07.898
and I actually ate night crawlers

19:07.981 --> 19:10.275
mixed with toothpaste and mustard.

19:10.359 --> 19:12.861
[friend] [on video] She's done.
She's ate all the worms.

19:12.945 --> 19:15.697
♪♪

19:15.781 --> 19:18.867
And it was horrible. Absolutely horrible.

19:18.951 --> 19:20.827
But I felt like I needed to be

19:20.911 --> 19:23.705
over the top in my creativity,

19:23.789 --> 19:26.333
because he was a big deal,

19:26.416 --> 19:28.919
and I wanted to stand out from the rest.

19:30.337 --> 19:33.006
He announces, you know, I can do a tour.

19:33.090 --> 19:34.383
I said yes.

19:34.466 --> 19:36.093
And I was over the moon excited.

19:36.176 --> 19:40.013
I was like, I guess, for some reason,
he liked my email.

19:40.097 --> 19:42.224
And he was very kind at that time.

19:42.307 --> 19:44.726
He made me feel like I was important

19:44.810 --> 19:46.937
and that I was already this huge celebrity

19:47.020 --> 19:48.522
and I had a fan base.

19:50.274 --> 19:51.859
You know, I'm gonna rock this.

19:51.942 --> 19:54.945
[♪ tense music playing]

19:58.115 --> 19:59.116
[wind chimes jingling]

20:07.040 --> 20:08.750
[jingling stops]

20:11.879 --> 20:14.715
I'm super scared.
I don't know who my partner is.

20:14.798 --> 20:17.593
Um, I'm waiting until it gets
a little closer to the time,

20:17.676 --> 20:19.845
then I'm gonna go sit
in the spot and wait.

20:19.928 --> 20:23.891
He said, "Find parking near the park.
There are bleachers. Sit at the bleachers,

20:23.974 --> 20:26.852
face forward.
Don't turn around or anything."

20:26.935 --> 20:30.689
And then, I went and met Russ at the park

20:30.772 --> 20:32.316
for my waiver signing.

20:32.399 --> 20:35.319
I was nervous. I was shaking.
My hands were trembling,

20:35.402 --> 20:38.280
and I was trying to fake that I was fine.

20:44.036 --> 20:45.037
[Brandon]
Sure.

20:45.913 --> 20:47.539
That was the infamous waiver.

20:47.623 --> 20:51.418
That was the waiver that
you're basically signing your life away.

20:51.502 --> 20:55.380
We're not responsible if you die.
Like, you're agreeing to sign up for this.

20:57.591 --> 20:58.592
No.

21:00.302 --> 21:02.763
-Yes, yes.
-Take this. Don't get it wet.

21:02.846 --> 21:05.432
Why are you doing this?
That's my question. Why would you do this

21:05.516 --> 21:08.310
after everything that's happening,
why would you sign this waiver?

21:08.393 --> 21:11.522
♪♪

21:11.605 --> 21:16.443
"Participant fully understands and agrees
that once participant enters MM,

21:16.527 --> 21:20.572
there is no quitting unless
serious psychological injury is present."

21:20.656 --> 21:23.242
Your hair may be chopped off.
Dentistry may be done.

21:23.325 --> 21:24.826
You may have a tooth extracted.

21:24.910 --> 21:27.996
"Head, neck, back injuries,
death, stroke,

21:28.080 --> 21:30.290
traumatic brain injury, brain aneurysm."

21:30.374 --> 21:32.626
I wasn't allowed to, like,
look at the person

21:32.709 --> 21:33.752
who gave us the waiver.

21:33.836 --> 21:35.420
We had very weird instructions.

21:35.504 --> 21:39.925
"Retinal hemorrhage, subdural hematoma,
loss of consciousness, whiplash,

21:40.008 --> 21:42.010
"harmful heart reactions,

21:42.094 --> 21:45.222
"nausea, headache, dizziness, lacerations,

21:45.305 --> 21:47.015
broken or sprained bones."

21:48.183 --> 21:50.143
[Melissa]
None of this had gotten to me.

21:51.478 --> 21:55.357
I had too much excitement
going through my veins at the time.

21:55.440 --> 21:58.402
If it would've said a man's
gonna come out of the woods

21:58.485 --> 22:01.488
and murder you during this event,
I-I would've signed it.

22:04.491 --> 22:07.494
[♪ tense music playing]

22:08.203 --> 22:09.454
[rustling papers]

22:16.753 --> 22:19.923
[Brandon] I get that feeling,
that adrenaline is just building,

22:20.007 --> 22:23.427
which is reminiscent right before
I left the wire when I was in Iraq.

22:23.510 --> 22:26.763
This was going outside of
the safety of your FOB.

22:27.973 --> 22:29.892
The FOB,
it's a forward operation base.

22:30.601 --> 22:32.394
That's where we lived.

22:32.477 --> 22:35.856
There's a clear delineation
of safety there. You know, safe,

22:37.274 --> 22:38.275
not safe.

22:39.610 --> 22:41.486
As soon as you go outside the gate...

22:41.570 --> 22:43.614
[♪ music building]

22:43.697 --> 22:46.033
-...adrenaline's as high as you can go.
-[explosion blasts]

22:46.116 --> 22:49.286
-[soldier] Yeah! Woo!
-[soldiers cheer]

22:49.369 --> 22:51.622
-[explosion]
-Yeah!

22:51.705 --> 22:54.291
[distant excited shouting]

22:54.374 --> 22:56.418
[♪ dramatic music playing]

22:56.502 --> 22:58.712
[Brandon]
We lost a lot of people over there.

22:58.795 --> 23:00.839
People were dying every single day.

23:02.633 --> 23:06.136
I did 21 years.
I did three combat tours in Iraq,

23:06.220 --> 23:08.639
which spanned over 40 months.

23:09.848 --> 23:12.643
At the start of the deployment,
I had hope.

23:14.228 --> 23:18.023
Very shortly, I realized
you abandon your hope.

23:18.941 --> 23:22.319
You realize that death
can come at any moment.

23:23.278 --> 23:24.780
♪♪

23:24.863 --> 23:27.449
[speaker 5]
Military experience is extreme.

23:27.533 --> 23:31.995
Terror haunt experience is extreme.
Anything that we do that is extreme,

23:32.079 --> 23:35.499
adrenaline, when it's coursing through us,
I mean, it makes us feel powerful.

23:35.582 --> 23:38.293
A lot of times when people
have had combat experiences,

23:38.377 --> 23:41.421
you cannot get that feeling anywhere else.

23:41.797 --> 23:44.174
-So, it almost gets kind of locked in.
-Mm.

23:44.258 --> 23:47.010
I'm Dr. Lindsay Bira,
clinical health psychologist

23:47.094 --> 23:49.763
and PTSD and trauma specialist.

23:49.847 --> 23:51.849
When somebody has had a trauma

23:51.932 --> 23:54.393
and their nervous system
is a little bit hijacked,

23:54.476 --> 23:56.103
like we see in PTSD,

23:56.186 --> 24:00.399
then it drives them to seek
external sensation to try to regulate.

24:02.401 --> 24:06.488
And for anybody with
anxiety, depression, PTSD,

24:06.572 --> 24:09.324
somebody experiencing
emotional abnormalities,

24:09.408 --> 24:13.120
they are more likely to
seek external stimulation.

24:13.203 --> 24:15.789
[birds cawing]

24:15.873 --> 24:18.542
I'm worried about these
types of experiences

24:18.625 --> 24:20.711
because there's no real structure.

24:20.794 --> 24:23.255
There's no limits.
The limits keep getting pushed.

24:23.338 --> 24:24.923
[screaming]

24:25.007 --> 24:28.343
But, the most important thing
is to be very careful

24:28.427 --> 24:32.306
who is leading an extreme experience.

24:33.140 --> 24:36.602
There can easily be abuse of power,

24:36.685 --> 24:39.813
and we don't know how
far to trust somebody.

24:39.897 --> 24:42.774
[♪ tense music playing]

24:45.777 --> 24:47.487
[Melissa]
He stuck me in his truck.

24:47.571 --> 24:50.449
Hey, everybody. Come on in.

24:50.532 --> 24:53.702
I was blindfolded,
I couldn't see anything,

24:53.785 --> 24:57.748
and off we went to the manor
to begin the tour.

25:01.126 --> 25:02.294
[breeze blowing]

25:02.377 --> 25:05.172
-[Brandon] He puts me into his truck.
-[door shuts]

25:05.255 --> 25:07.674
He puts earphones on me,

25:07.758 --> 25:11.595
and then I remember
the sounds of babies crying,

25:11.678 --> 25:14.056
-and it's very, very loud.
-[babies cry]

25:15.307 --> 25:18.727
I'm like, "Okay, I've just lost
my sense of hearing."

25:18.810 --> 25:22.189
-And then, he starts duct taping my head.
-[tape ripping]

25:22.272 --> 25:25.108
He covers my entire head with duct tape,

25:25.192 --> 25:26.443
that I bought, mind you.

25:26.527 --> 25:29.947
Once they kidnapped us and put us
in the van, that's when I, like,

25:30.030 --> 25:31.615
I don't even think I felt anxious.

25:31.698 --> 25:33.951
I think I was in, like,
fight or flight mode,

25:34.034 --> 25:36.495
and I had to fight 'cause there was
nowhere that I could go.

25:36.578 --> 25:38.455
So I was just very focused.

25:38.539 --> 25:40.040
[♪ intense music playing]

25:40.123 --> 25:42.000
[Brandon]
I don't know what to expect.

25:42.084 --> 25:45.170
I knew this was go time, right?

25:45.254 --> 25:48.757
I'm getting what I've been
wanting to do for years.

25:48.841 --> 25:50.884
It's time!
Then, the door swings open.

25:50.968 --> 25:52.386
Come over here.

25:52.469 --> 25:54.638
I was so focused
because he was filming me.

25:54.721 --> 25:57.391
I had camera fright.

25:57.474 --> 26:00.561
This video's live, and so
it was very, very scary.

26:00.644 --> 26:03.313
[Russ] Fans, what color would
you like her base to be?

26:03.397 --> 26:05.774
You got purple, red, pink, yellow.

26:05.858 --> 26:07.776
[Melissa]
He hyped me up, did lives,

26:07.860 --> 26:09.695
and he's reading off the comments.

26:09.778 --> 26:12.364
[Russ]
She's a sport. Guys, she's a sport.

26:12.447 --> 26:16.243
[Kris] You're gonna be the best one,
you're gonna put on the best show ever.

26:16.326 --> 26:20.122
Hypes it up all the time. Really gets
you going, gets the fans going.

26:20.205 --> 26:24.042
And then, that-that starts to get
into, you know, your ego.

26:24.126 --> 26:25.419
You're like, "Oh, my God,

26:25.502 --> 26:28.505
"I got thousands of people watching me.
I was a nobody,

26:28.589 --> 26:31.258
I-- and now I got people rooting me on?"

26:31.341 --> 26:33.802
And you don't wanna let 'em down.

26:33.886 --> 26:36.096
♪♪

26:36.180 --> 26:37.723
They pushed us out of the van.

26:37.806 --> 26:40.017
And I think we had to crawl
through, like, chicken wire.

26:40.100 --> 26:41.935
They had, like, some maze
through a garage.

26:45.147 --> 26:47.858
When we got to the other side,
that's when we met Russ,

26:47.941 --> 26:50.777
and he looked so happy, so excited.

26:50.861 --> 26:53.530
He had a big old flashlight
with a camera on his head.

26:53.614 --> 26:55.073
[panting]

26:55.157 --> 26:57.701
In the moment,
just the way he's, like, talking about it

26:57.784 --> 27:01.205
and the tone of his voice as he's
talking about it as it's happening.

27:01.288 --> 27:04.750
[Russ] [on TV] Are you prepared?
Good. This is your one chance.

27:04.833 --> 27:08.045
I'm gonna give you an out.
If you want out, you can get out now.

27:08.128 --> 27:10.964
-[haunter] Verbalize.
-No, I wanna stay in.

27:11.048 --> 27:13.884
[Russ] Okay, that's what I like.
Okay, cover her eyes.

27:13.967 --> 27:16.803
[inaudible]

27:23.852 --> 27:26.855
[♪ creepy music playing]

27:28.398 --> 27:30.442
It was definitely an endurance test.

27:30.526 --> 27:32.528
-[splashing]
-[groaning]

27:40.160 --> 27:43.372
[Russ] Wall climb! Batman time!
Batman time!

27:44.414 --> 27:47.793
There is no EMTs. There are no medics.

27:47.876 --> 27:49.586
What happens if you're in a stunt,

27:49.670 --> 27:53.131
and somethin' happens to him,
and he's hurt? You could be tied up.

27:53.215 --> 27:56.677
Y-You're stuck, nobody's gonna find you.

27:56.760 --> 27:58.971
-[haunter] Oh! No, you go in there!
-[Gabi screams]

27:59.054 --> 28:01.056
-[rustling]
-[haunter] Sit!

28:02.558 --> 28:06.019
Next thing I know, he grabs my chest
and dunks my head under water.

28:06.937 --> 28:08.397
And he holds my chest there.

28:08.480 --> 28:09.982
♪♪

28:11.733 --> 28:13.735
I'm thinking, "If I just hold my breath

28:13.819 --> 28:15.779
"and don't think, stop moving,

28:15.863 --> 28:18.240
he'll eventually pull me back up",
which he does.

28:18.323 --> 28:20.325
And then I start gasping for air again.

28:20.409 --> 28:22.661
And then he does it
five or six more times.

28:22.744 --> 28:24.246
[dripping]

28:26.582 --> 28:28.417
[Gabi]
What if this isn't fake?

28:28.500 --> 28:30.627
What if I'm really trapped
in this-this freezer now?

28:30.711 --> 28:34.047
Like, and I'm at this guy's house,
I don't know where I'm at location-wise.

28:34.131 --> 28:37.801
-[Gabi] [screams] Let me out!
-[haunter] [laughs] Louder!

28:37.885 --> 28:41.346
So, that just all happened in my mind,
and I just had a panic attack.

28:41.430 --> 28:43.682
-Let me out!
-[haunter] You want out?

28:43.765 --> 28:47.186
-Oh, you crying? I think she was crying!
-[Gabi sniffling]

28:47.269 --> 28:49.771
Oh, beautiful tears, yes!

28:50.647 --> 28:53.650
-Oh, look at this. Look at the camera.
-[sniffles]

28:53.734 --> 28:55.235
Look at camera!

28:56.612 --> 28:57.821
[crying] I wanna get out.

28:58.780 --> 29:01.867
[Russ] This is just the beginning.
You understand that, right?

29:01.950 --> 29:04.536
There's so many dark places
you're gonna go tonight.

29:04.620 --> 29:07.623
♪♪

29:09.124 --> 29:12.085
[Gabi] There's a certain point
where they put us in straitjackets

29:12.169 --> 29:14.713
with chains over our neck,
and I was like, "Oh gosh,

29:14.796 --> 29:16.423
this is uncomfortable and it's heavy."

29:19.843 --> 29:22.804
And then that's when the
water boarding proceeded to happen.

29:22.888 --> 29:24.932
[Russ]
Put your head in there.

29:25.015 --> 29:27.017
[water splashing]

29:28.852 --> 29:29.978
[coughing]

29:31.230 --> 29:32.272
[choking]

29:32.356 --> 29:35.734
[inaudible]

29:35.817 --> 29:39.613
[Gabi] I was like, "Oh, this is what
it means to be waterboarded.

29:39.696 --> 29:42.115
I feel like I'm drowning."

29:42.199 --> 29:43.367
[coughing]

29:43.450 --> 29:46.662
[Russ] So, you're gonna have to be
looking for the big baby bottle.

29:46.870 --> 29:49.081
-[splashing]
-Yeah, go.

29:49.164 --> 29:51.500
-[Melissa] Ew... Oh...
-[Russ] Get on your belly.

29:51.583 --> 29:53.961
-Get on your belly!
-[splashing]

29:54.044 --> 29:56.213
I'm terrified of spiders.
Like, to the point

29:56.296 --> 29:59.758
where if I even see one across the room,
I get, like, a rash, and I just get itchy

29:59.842 --> 30:02.302
'cause I just cannot stand them.
And he knew that.

30:02.386 --> 30:04.847
He asked me going in,
like, what my biggest fear was.

30:04.930 --> 30:07.933
♪♪

30:09.226 --> 30:12.688
-[Gabi whimpers]
-[Russ] [on TV] Shh. Don't make any noise.

30:12.771 --> 30:14.106
Shh...

30:14.189 --> 30:15.732
Don't make any quick motion.

30:15.816 --> 30:17.609
[Gabi] [on TV]
[sobs] Please, no.

30:17.693 --> 30:20.070
They were telling me that
the tarantula was mad,

30:20.153 --> 30:21.530
and I didn't know that, like,

30:21.613 --> 30:23.824
you're not supposed
to handle tarantulas like that.

30:23.907 --> 30:26.118
So he could-- the tarantula,
like, could've gotten mad

30:26.201 --> 30:28.579
and like, at me, and bit me, I guess.

30:28.662 --> 30:31.665
So they were like, "Don't cry.
Quit freaking out, don't cry."

30:31.748 --> 30:33.792
And I was like,
"You have a spider on my face.

30:33.876 --> 30:35.919
How am I not supposed to cry?"
And then he's like,

30:36.003 --> 30:37.212
"We're gonna do it anyway.

30:37.296 --> 30:39.047
So like, if you cry,
you're gonna get hurt."

30:39.131 --> 30:42.009
So like, in the video, I just froze.
I think I just like, stopped breathing,

30:42.092 --> 30:44.386
and I just, like, had an
out of body experience.

30:44.469 --> 30:46.805
[crying] Please don't. Please.

30:46.889 --> 30:50.058
[Russ] Look at her.
Look at her, Mary, look at her.

30:50.142 --> 30:52.436
-[Haunter Mary] Isn't she pretty?
-Please! [gasping]

30:52.519 --> 30:55.189
-[Russ] Look at her.
-Please don't.

30:55.272 --> 30:57.316
-Please.
-[Haunter Mary] Oops. Oops.

30:57.399 --> 30:59.651
Please don't. Please don't. Please don't!

30:59.735 --> 31:01.820
-[Russ] Shh...
-[Gabi whimpering]

31:01.904 --> 31:04.489
It was, like, that moment that
it kind of shifted for me.

31:04.573 --> 31:08.327
[inaudible]

31:08.410 --> 31:11.038
[♪ tense music playing]

31:11.121 --> 31:12.456
[screams]

31:12.539 --> 31:15.000
I think I'd went seven, eight hours.

31:15.083 --> 31:16.835
-[splashing]
-[Melissa groaning]

31:16.919 --> 31:18.712
[Russ]
Find that baby bottle.

31:18.795 --> 31:19.838
[clicking]

31:20.756 --> 31:24.301
Alright, guys.
She's doing really good tonight.

31:24.384 --> 31:27.513
[Melissa] But, in that moment,
I'm like the celebrity.

31:27.596 --> 31:29.014
I have this huge fan base.

31:29.097 --> 31:31.517
That was big for me. That was huge.

31:31.600 --> 31:34.603
She's a trooper,
and she wants to continue on, so,

31:34.686 --> 31:37.314
so we're just,
we're doing stuff right now.

31:37.397 --> 31:39.525
[Haunter Mary]
You're a rock star.

31:39.608 --> 31:42.027
He closed this cage gate on top of me,

31:42.110 --> 31:44.029
and this water was freezing cold.

31:44.112 --> 31:46.198
And he said,

31:46.281 --> 31:49.284
"Okay, I'm gonna start
raising the water level."

31:49.368 --> 31:52.371
When I could start feeling the water rise
and when I remember

31:52.454 --> 31:54.706
I tried to put resistance on the cage,

31:54.790 --> 31:56.834
and I-- it wouldn't budge,

31:58.001 --> 32:00.254
that's when I just, I was like,
I'm done. I'm done.

32:03.799 --> 32:05.759
-Exactly, exactly.
-I ended up quitting.

32:05.843 --> 32:09.179
-[Russ] You got punished here.
-[Haunter Mary] This is her punishment

32:09.263 --> 32:11.473
for not findin' the baby bottle.

32:11.557 --> 32:14.101
-[Russ] McKamey Manor just what?
-McKamey Manor just kicked my ass.

32:14.184 --> 32:15.602
-[Russ] And you quit.
-And I quit.

32:15.686 --> 32:19.147
-[Brandon] I didn't wanna die.
-[Gabi] [crying] I'm done.

32:19.231 --> 32:21.066
-[Russ] Tell me you quit.
-[Gabi] I quit.

32:21.149 --> 32:23.443
I don't wanna be
locked in the dark anymore.

32:23.527 --> 32:25.904
Russ is there the entire time,
recording it.

32:25.988 --> 32:29.408
And the joy and, like, pleasure

32:29.491 --> 32:33.078
that he was getting out of it
was extremely weird.

32:33.161 --> 32:35.247
You could see he was unfazed.

32:35.330 --> 32:39.626
I'm here, bawling, I'm bleeding,
and you're just living your best life,

32:39.710 --> 32:42.462
trying to figure out how much
further you could take it.

32:42.546 --> 32:44.756
And I'm just-- that's concerning to me.

32:44.840 --> 32:47.926
But in the moment, I was like,
"Oh, this is Russ, this is the guy.

32:48.010 --> 32:50.387
He has the camera on his head.
Let's do the tour."

32:50.929 --> 32:53.140
[Brandon]
Some of these other extreme haunts,

32:53.223 --> 32:56.977
the trust that I've given them
has not been broken.

32:57.060 --> 33:00.939
Even though I'm telling them to push,
even though I'm telling them

33:01.023 --> 33:04.776
to do worse and worse stuff to me,
I think, deep down,

33:05.485 --> 33:07.571
I know that they're not gonna kill me.

33:07.654 --> 33:10.240
You know,
I know they're not gonna cause

33:10.324 --> 33:13.410
permanent physical danger,

33:13.493 --> 33:17.372
but trust was broken with Russ McKamey.

33:17.456 --> 33:20.459
[♪ tense music playing]

33:20.542 --> 33:21.710
[inaudible]

33:22.252 --> 33:24.546
[Gabi] My experience was fucked up,
but I also am aware

33:24.630 --> 33:27.090
that every experience after mine

33:27.174 --> 33:30.636
was a thousand times worse
because I think he did see

33:30.719 --> 33:33.931
that he kind of was able
to keep us for seven hours,

33:34.014 --> 33:37.476
and kind of do whatever he wanted,
and, like, we didn't do anything about it.

33:37.559 --> 33:40.479
We just, like, left and said,
"Thanks so much, have a great time."

33:40.562 --> 33:43.482
So I think for him that was validation.
Like, "Oh, I could do more."

33:43.565 --> 33:45.067
[♪ dramatic music playing]

33:45.150 --> 33:49.029
[Russ] Hey, everybody, it's Russ. Coming
at you right here from McKamey Manor.

33:49.112 --> 33:53.575
[Brandon] Never come here.
Don't let-- Don't let anybody

33:53.659 --> 33:55.827
talk you into it or any of that

33:55.911 --> 33:58.622
because it's, um, it's brutal.

33:58.730 --> 34:00.208
[♪ dramatic sting]

34:00.290 --> 34:03.293
-[quiet street noise]
-[insects chirping]

34:06.088 --> 34:07.464
[Melissa]
The "why."

34:08.966 --> 34:10.968
[♪ unsettling music playing]

34:11.051 --> 34:14.054
[TV static]

34:15.806 --> 34:17.766
Everybody's always
gonna wonder the why,

34:17.850 --> 34:21.812
and the why is different for each
and every individual that goes through.

34:28.527 --> 34:30.028
My name is DJ Williams.

34:30.112 --> 34:33.115
I'm a full professor at
Idaho State University

34:33.198 --> 34:34.783
in Pocatello, Idaho.

34:34.867 --> 34:38.662
I was given the title Dr. Deviant
from a dominatrix who I mentored under.

34:40.163 --> 34:42.374
And my research covers sort of the range

34:42.457 --> 34:44.585
and spectrum of deviance and leisure,

34:44.668 --> 34:47.045
and that can include
a lot of different things.

34:47.129 --> 34:49.965
That can include criminal activity
as leisure.

34:50.048 --> 34:54.011
It can include BDSM
and sexuality as leisure.

34:54.887 --> 34:58.515
The extreme horror,
extreme experiences phenomenon,

34:58.599 --> 35:01.393
definitely fits within the area
of deviant leisure.

35:02.686 --> 35:04.605
And it's hard for people to understand

35:04.688 --> 35:08.650
someone who is clearly an intense
sensation seeker or risk taker

35:08.734 --> 35:11.486
that those challenges are actual needs.

35:11.570 --> 35:14.907
And so, we need to have a space,
an, an acceptance for people

35:14.990 --> 35:17.034
who are craving those kinds of needs.

35:17.117 --> 35:20.162
So, I think it's easy for, sometimes
people to kinda sit back and say,

35:20.245 --> 35:24.082
"Why would somebody do this?
There must be something wrong with them."

35:24.166 --> 35:26.627
And that's not the case, necessarily.

35:27.002 --> 35:29.755
♪♪

35:29.838 --> 35:32.591
[Gabi]
I grew up in private Christian school.

35:32.674 --> 35:35.344
I grew up hearing if you lie,
you're gonna go to Hell.

35:35.427 --> 35:37.554
And it wasn't just, like,
you're gonna go to Hell.

35:37.638 --> 35:41.016
It's like, "Your skin is gonna burn off,
and your eyes are gonna melt."

35:41.099 --> 35:42.351
And I'm, like, 5.

35:43.560 --> 35:47.314
I am queer, so being Black-queer
in a space like that,

35:47.397 --> 35:49.608
was really hard to
navigate as, like, a young kid.

35:49.691 --> 35:52.402
It's, like, pro-conversion therapy,
"Let's get that out of you.

35:52.486 --> 35:54.863
This isn't natural.
You're living a life of sin."

35:54.947 --> 35:57.950
So just growing up hearing that,
I didn't even know that it was okay.

35:58.033 --> 35:59.910
I didn't even know what queer was.

35:59.993 --> 36:02.454
I just knew that, like,
I was really different.

36:02.538 --> 36:05.207
I just knew that it was bad and evil.

36:05.290 --> 36:08.460
To this day, like, I have anxiety 24/7,

36:08.544 --> 36:10.671
so, like, even right now,
my heart's like... [exhales].

36:10.754 --> 36:13.549
It used to be so bad where
I couldn't go to the grocery store,

36:13.632 --> 36:15.050
I would just like sit in my car

36:15.133 --> 36:17.553
'cause just I felt
too overwhelmed with everything.

36:17.636 --> 36:20.973
So, when I watch a horror film,
I have that same feeling,

36:21.056 --> 36:24.309
but it's safely on my couch,
and it makes sense.

36:24.393 --> 36:25.394
♪♪

36:25.477 --> 36:28.480
It's like, oh, there's a guy
with a chainsaw on the TV,

36:28.564 --> 36:29.857
like, gonna hurt somebody.

36:29.940 --> 36:31.984
There's a reason
to be anxious in this moment.

36:32.901 --> 36:34.695
Which is why I started looking into

36:34.778 --> 36:37.030
the whole immersive horror
experience thing.

36:37.114 --> 36:39.992
So, I was like,
"What if I live through something crazy"

36:40.075 --> 36:43.120
and then I know that I can
do anything going forward.

36:43.203 --> 36:44.580
It reminds me, "Hey,

36:44.663 --> 36:48.250
"I just went through
this series of events,

36:48.333 --> 36:49.543
and I survived."

36:49.626 --> 36:53.172
[insects chirping]

36:54.173 --> 36:56.800
As a young child,

36:57.593 --> 37:00.387
I dealt with an abusive mother.

37:00.470 --> 37:01.513
♪♪

37:01.597 --> 37:04.391
Being put into a foster home
at such a young age

37:04.474 --> 37:06.852
was very, very traumatic.

37:07.603 --> 37:11.398
It was scary having to go through
people and people and people,

37:11.481 --> 37:15.485
and tell the same story over
and over again of what happened.

37:15.569 --> 37:17.404
To be one day ripped apart

37:17.487 --> 37:20.073
from everyone you know and everything.

37:20.157 --> 37:23.076
To be told you're taken to a safer place,

37:24.036 --> 37:27.998
and the place you're going to
is just full of unknown and uncertainty,

37:28.081 --> 37:31.084
and it just breaks a part of you inside.

37:32.336 --> 37:35.339
I feel like I do these things
to remind myself

37:35.422 --> 37:38.133
that I'm strong, and I'm a survivor,

37:38.217 --> 37:40.677
and I can get through a lot of shit.

37:40.761 --> 37:43.055
♪♪

37:43.138 --> 37:45.057
[W.P.]
A lot of people go through

37:45.140 --> 37:47.184
really traumatic situations,

37:47.267 --> 37:50.771
and they find something to fill this gap.

37:50.854 --> 37:54.816
And I would see the progress of making it
through something that's terrible

37:54.900 --> 37:57.611
and-and using it to the
advantage of yourself.

37:59.738 --> 38:00.989
[♪ dramatic crescendo]

38:02.407 --> 38:06.620
It sounds like there's a lot of,
kind of pushing, or here's an edge,

38:06.703 --> 38:08.872
but then, "Okay,
I can go beyond that edge.

38:08.956 --> 38:11.416
I just accomplished this.
I guess let's take it further."

38:11.500 --> 38:15.170
Like, I feel like I need--
Like, I need that type of punishment.

38:15.254 --> 38:16.463
Mm-hmm.

38:16.547 --> 38:18.549
Like it's something that--

38:19.508 --> 38:21.635
it's something that I feel like I deserve.

38:21.718 --> 38:23.554
[♪ soft music playing]

38:23.637 --> 38:26.640
When I got back,
I was a completely different person.

38:26.723 --> 38:29.393
Okay and that was after you came back
from the military, right?

38:29.476 --> 38:31.061
Yes, that was after my

38:31.144 --> 38:32.729
-third tour in Iraq.
-Okay.

38:32.813 --> 38:36.984
I didn't see here as home.
This wasn't home to me anymore.

38:38.277 --> 38:40.779
I think I knew I had PTSD.

38:40.863 --> 38:43.365
I sure as hell didn't think
I had survivor's guilt,

38:43.448 --> 38:46.118
but one of the things I did is,

38:46.201 --> 38:48.537
I started giving away body parts.

38:48.620 --> 38:50.038
I gave my kidney away.

38:50.122 --> 38:53.667
I was also signed up to give
a piece of my liver away.

38:53.750 --> 38:56.670
And I also signed up
for the bone marrow transplant list.

38:56.753 --> 38:58.505
[♪ tense music playing]

38:58.589 --> 39:00.716
I was gonna give away as much as I could.

39:02.050 --> 39:04.219
I didn't see any purpose anymore.

39:06.180 --> 39:08.557
There's parts of me that
are essentially broken, you know,

39:08.640 --> 39:11.059
and, emotionally, mentally, physically,
what have you.

39:11.143 --> 39:14.313
[Dr. Lindsay Bira]
It's not a bad thing to push the limits

39:14.396 --> 39:17.065
or to, you know, have a very real
human experience

39:17.149 --> 39:19.318
or to explore the edges
of human experience.

39:19.401 --> 39:22.237
I think that's actually an awesome thing.

39:22.321 --> 39:25.824
But, you are desensitizing yourself
to those natural cues,

39:25.908 --> 39:28.911
where your brain and your body
is saying, "This is my limit."

39:30.204 --> 39:31.288
Yeah.

39:31.371 --> 39:34.166
[Dr. Bira] That's something
really good to think about.

39:35.167 --> 39:38.170
Well, I mean, I just look
at those ultra-marathon runners, right?

39:38.253 --> 39:42.174
They punish their body.
Their feet are torn to pieces, you know?

39:42.257 --> 39:45.677
It's all in the name of,
you know, self-improvement.

39:48.138 --> 39:50.557
[Dr. Deviant]
You have big wave surfers,

39:50.641 --> 39:54.019
you have freestyle mountain climbers
who use no safety gear,

39:54.102 --> 39:56.104
deep ocean divers,

39:56.188 --> 39:58.482
and they're constantly pushing that edge.

39:58.565 --> 40:00.442
[Brandon]
Why is this any different?

40:00.526 --> 40:03.487
I could never run an ultra marathon.
I know I can't.

40:03.570 --> 40:05.656
But, I can, I can get tortured
for 12 hours.

40:05.739 --> 40:07.574
[Russ]
The fun has just begun.

40:07.658 --> 40:11.286
So far, what you've endured
is nothing compared to the last half.

40:11.370 --> 40:14.581
-[♪ dramatic music playing]
-[whimpering]

40:14.665 --> 40:18.168
[speaker 6]
Torture is the intentional infliction

40:18.252 --> 40:22.172
of serious or severe pain
and suffering

40:22.256 --> 40:24.383
-on a person...
-[dripping]

40:24.466 --> 40:26.552
...for the purpose of punishment

40:26.635 --> 40:29.096
or to force them to do or say something.

40:31.265 --> 40:32.891
My name is Alka Pradhan.

40:32.975 --> 40:36.061
I'm a human rights attorney
practicing at Guantanamo Bay

40:36.144 --> 40:38.355
and before the International
Criminal Court.

40:38.438 --> 40:41.733
And my expertise is in
working with torture victims.

40:42.693 --> 40:47.322
And in my work at Guantanamo Bay,
I'm employed by the Department of Defense.

40:47.406 --> 40:49.950
And so, nothing I say represents

40:50.033 --> 40:52.327
the opinion of the Department of Defense.

40:52.411 --> 40:55.789
And nothing I say should be taken
to confirm or deny any information

40:55.873 --> 40:58.917
that the Department of Defense
considers to be classified.

40:59.001 --> 41:02.963
Personally, I am really repulsed

41:03.046 --> 41:07.009
by the idea of anyone using torture

41:07.092 --> 41:10.304
or acts that simulate torture

41:10.387 --> 41:13.182
in a way that is entertaining.

41:13.265 --> 41:14.766
[lock clicking]

41:15.392 --> 41:18.353
Nothing about torture is entertaining.

41:18.437 --> 41:21.690
Undergoing torture doesn't
really strengthen you.

41:21.773 --> 41:23.275
If it doesn't kill people,

41:23.358 --> 41:26.236
it affects them for the entirety
of their lives.

41:27.279 --> 41:29.948
The first thing to keep in mind is that

41:30.866 --> 41:32.367
♪♪

41:32.451 --> 41:34.286
all torture has
psychological effects.

41:34.536 --> 41:38.290
Even if you consent
to some aspect of that,

41:38.373 --> 41:40.709
the fear created in your mind,

41:41.835 --> 41:45.297
what psychologists often call
"uncontrollable stress,"

41:46.048 --> 41:48.342
can literally change your neural pathways.

41:48.425 --> 41:51.595
And it's something that is
almost impossible to remove.

41:51.678 --> 41:53.805
[♪ dramatic music playing]

41:55.057 --> 41:57.851
[Russ] So, did-did you expect
all that after, you know?

41:57.935 --> 42:01.188
Well, I expected it to be rough,
but I didn't expect to actually cry.

42:01.271 --> 42:04.900
[♪ dramatic crescendo]

42:05.317 --> 42:08.070
-[Russ] Yeah, you did cry.
-[Gabi] Yeah, like five times.

42:09.238 --> 42:11.240
[♪ soft ominous tone]

42:11.323 --> 42:14.785
[Gabi] Russ posted my video on YouTube,
and it went super viral.

42:15.786 --> 42:19.748
[♪ dissonant chords playing]

42:20.749 --> 42:22.918
A few months after going through it,

42:23.001 --> 42:25.337
I, so bad, just wanted to be involved

42:25.420 --> 42:27.339
with, like, anything to do with horror.

42:27.422 --> 42:30.425
Whether it was, like, acting
or, like, writing or anything.

42:31.426 --> 42:33.095
And Russ saw that.

42:34.012 --> 42:37.641
And I ended up running his Facebook group,
I was running his YouTube channel,

42:37.724 --> 42:40.310
I was running his Twitter.
I was like his little assistant.

42:40.394 --> 42:43.063
Get people into the haunt, hype it up.

42:43.146 --> 42:45.274
If people were talking
negatively about it,

42:45.357 --> 42:47.276
I was supposed to, like, undercut them.

42:47.359 --> 42:50.195
Be like, "No, like, I've met Russ.
He's, like, such a great guy."

42:50.279 --> 42:53.407
So, I was just supposed to
be his, like, wingman.

42:54.658 --> 42:57.911
But then, I started to
get some weird feelings.

42:57.995 --> 42:59.746
Um,

42:59.830 --> 43:03.292
I'm just gonna keep this short.
It's actually hard to talk.

43:03.375 --> 43:07.337
As you can see,
my lips are severely swollen.

43:07.421 --> 43:09.631
He likes men that have
been in the military.

43:09.715 --> 43:13.468
I think Russ really got off
on, like, the power dynamic with the men.

43:13.552 --> 43:16.013
[muffled screaming]

43:16.096 --> 43:18.098
There are some tours where

43:18.182 --> 43:21.435
the way that they were
beat up was just too-- like, too far.

43:21.518 --> 43:24.062
Like, broken ribs, concussions,

43:24.146 --> 43:26.398
like, eyes so swollen that
they can't even open 'em.

43:26.481 --> 43:29.109
[♪ tense music playing]

43:29.193 --> 43:30.611
And I think for him, it's power.

43:30.694 --> 43:33.405
Like, "This guy was in the Marines?
Like, look at me kicking his ass."

43:38.035 --> 43:41.330
-And then, like, vulnerable women.
-No, Russ, that water freaks me out.

43:41.413 --> 43:43.582
-You know that! I hate--
-[water hose hissing]

43:43.665 --> 43:45.709
[crying] Please! Please, don't!

43:45.792 --> 43:48.629
Russ feels that if you go
through one of his experiences,

43:48.712 --> 43:52.049
especially if you're female,
you now have a special bond with Russ.

43:52.132 --> 43:55.552
He really only wanted, like, pretty girls.

43:55.636 --> 43:57.137
[rattling]

43:57.221 --> 43:59.556
No. No! No.

43:59.640 --> 44:01.225
[Russ]
Honey, be quiet.

44:01.308 --> 44:03.560
[rattling]

44:03.644 --> 44:07.606
You knew when he had a new girlfriend
because it was nonstop shows.

44:07.689 --> 44:10.234
He would have them come to his house,

44:10.317 --> 44:12.402
and he would just make them

44:12.486 --> 44:14.905
continuously go through a tour

44:14.988 --> 44:16.698
every day that they were with him.

44:16.782 --> 44:19.409
♪♪

44:19.493 --> 44:22.412
-[whimpering, sobbing]
-[Kris] For some reasons, he feels like

44:22.496 --> 44:24.706
with these women he can go an extra step,

44:24.790 --> 44:28.293
and that safety harness just
gets removed a little more.

44:28.377 --> 44:31.755
[Susan] Things like laying in the grass
with a ski mask on my face,

44:31.839 --> 44:33.924
getting sprayed with water over and over,

44:34.007 --> 44:37.094
or submerging into cold water
over and over.

44:37.177 --> 44:38.887
And in one particular activity,

44:38.971 --> 44:41.723
I confessed that I was
actually afraid of dying.

44:41.807 --> 44:44.852
And he laughed and said that if I died,

44:44.935 --> 44:46.478
at least I would be on camera.

44:46.562 --> 44:48.397
♪♪

44:48.480 --> 44:50.607
[Kris]
These are really good-looking women.

44:50.691 --> 44:52.818
And you got this guy
who lives in a trailer

44:52.901 --> 44:54.903
that sprays you in the face with a hose.

44:54.987 --> 44:58.740
What is he doing to keep 'em to stay?

44:59.324 --> 45:01.285
-I don't know.
-[Russ] I like that.

45:01.368 --> 45:04.371
-[dog barking]
-[Russ] There she is!

45:04.454 --> 45:07.457
There she is! The pretty one right there.

45:07.541 --> 45:09.710
[Brandon]
McKamey Manor was "Tinder" to him.

45:09.793 --> 45:11.128
Was his "Plenty of Fish."

45:11.211 --> 45:14.214
That's what he used it for.
That's the impression that I got.

45:14.298 --> 45:16.383
You can do this.
Put your head up, please.

45:17.843 --> 45:20.012
You got this, okay? You got it.

45:20.095 --> 45:24.016
He was my friend. Like, I don't want
to think that he would actually

45:24.099 --> 45:27.686
purposely manipulate
these women, but he does.

45:27.769 --> 45:30.272
Show 'em what you got in your mouth.

45:30.355 --> 45:32.941
-Ah, ah, ah! [giggle]
-That's right.

45:33.025 --> 45:35.819
-Come here, and you can wear that, too.
-Yep!

45:35.903 --> 45:37.988
He knows how to get into people's heads,

45:38.071 --> 45:42.075
he knows the right thing to say,
he can read a person really good.

45:42.492 --> 45:45.204
I've seen Russ talk to a person

45:45.287 --> 45:48.415
that hates everything about the haunt,

45:48.498 --> 45:50.667
and turn them into a friend by the end

45:50.751 --> 45:52.169
and wanting to sign up.

45:52.252 --> 45:55.047
He-He is so good at what he does.

45:55.130 --> 45:57.966
Yeah, I'm that big crazy
haunted house guy! That's me!

45:58.050 --> 46:00.886
-[girlfriend laughs]
-Are you scared of me?

46:00.969 --> 46:02.554
I'm pretty scary, aren't I?

46:02.638 --> 46:05.849
-[♪ soft music playing]
-[TV static]

46:05.933 --> 46:08.519
[Kris] You know, he would try
to manipulate me, too.

46:09.728 --> 46:12.231
-[indistinct sound]
-[water splashing]

46:13.190 --> 46:14.983
When I went through,

46:15.984 --> 46:19.947
Russ had me sit back in, like, a trough.

46:20.030 --> 46:22.241
-[clattering]
-[shivering]

46:22.324 --> 46:24.993
-[Russ] Yeah. You like that?
-[Kris] No.

46:26.078 --> 46:30.332
[Russ] We're gonna fill up this entire
little device right here.

46:30.415 --> 46:32.417
[water dripping]

46:32.501 --> 46:34.586
And we're gonna have a good time, Kris.

46:34.670 --> 46:36.255
-[Kris groans]
-Oh, yeah.

46:36.338 --> 46:40.759
When I started to realize that I was
having the dirt poured over my face...

46:40.843 --> 46:43.887
-No, no, no, no, no.
-[Russ sighs]

46:43.971 --> 46:45.681
-[Kris groans]
-How's that feel?

46:45.764 --> 46:46.765
[Kris]
No, no, no, no.

46:46.849 --> 46:49.184
...and then you're thinking,
"Russ is my friend."

46:49.268 --> 46:52.312
You know, "He's-He's just gonna make
it look good for the camera."

46:53.021 --> 46:54.523
But then, he didn't stop.

46:54.606 --> 46:56.942
-No, no, no, no, no... [continues]
-[Russ] Who's your friend?

46:57.025 --> 46:58.861
-Quiet, shut up. Shut up.
-[Kris stops]

46:58.944 --> 47:00.529
And I can't even tell you

47:00.612 --> 47:03.532
the amount of times in that video
that I said "Stop."

47:03.615 --> 47:05.868
-[Russ] We're gonna bury you completely.
-[digs]

47:05.951 --> 47:08.245
[Kris] Mm-mm. No,
I can't do it. Can't do it.

47:08.328 --> 47:10.622
-No, I can't do it.
-[Russ] You gotta be quiet.

47:10.706 --> 47:12.749
-Be quiet!
-[Kris] No, I'm freaking out.

47:12.833 --> 47:15.043
-[Russ] You're not freaking out.
-[Kris] [spits] No!

47:15.127 --> 47:17.504
I was done. Game over.

47:17.588 --> 47:20.716
And it just kept going
and going and going.

47:20.799 --> 47:23.760
And in that moment,
I didn't know if it was gonna stop.

47:23.844 --> 47:25.971
[Russ] We have hours
and hours to go, Kris.

47:26.054 --> 47:27.848
[Kris]
No, no, no. Russ, no.

47:27.931 --> 47:29.766
-No more, no more.
-[Russ] You're fine.

47:29.850 --> 47:31.727
-Be quiet.
-[Kris] I quit, I quit.

47:31.810 --> 47:33.604
[Russ] You don't quit.
There is no quitting.

47:33.687 --> 47:35.689
-[Kris] [spits] No.
-[Russ] There is no quitting, Kris.

47:35.772 --> 47:38.233
I-I started to question,
"Is this the end?"

47:38.317 --> 47:39.610
I-I can't get out of this.

47:39.693 --> 47:42.905
I was stuck in a spot that
I was not moving from.

47:42.988 --> 47:45.490
[Russ]
I wanna bury you completely. Completely.

47:45.574 --> 47:48.118
[Kris]
No, I can't. I can't. I can't. I can't.

47:48.202 --> 47:50.662
-Russ, I can't. Russ, I can't.
-[Russ yells, laughs]

47:50.746 --> 47:53.624
-I quit. Russ, I quit. I can't.
-[Russ] There's no quitting.

47:53.707 --> 47:56.043
-[Kris] Russ, I-- [spits]
-[Russ] Ooh there!

47:56.126 --> 47:59.713
That doubt starts to seep into your head,
and you're thinkin',

47:59.796 --> 48:02.382
"I didn't say goodbye to people.
Why did I come here?

48:02.466 --> 48:04.593
"Why did I go against that
better judgment?

48:04.676 --> 48:08.639
Am I finally gonna be the one
that the line is crossed for?"

48:10.724 --> 48:12.351
You really don't wanna do this.

48:12.434 --> 48:14.728
[Kris panting]

48:15.062 --> 48:17.981
[Russ] So tell the folks about
whether they should come here or not.

48:18.065 --> 48:20.275
[Kris] No, don't go.
Don't come here. Don't sign up.

48:20.359 --> 48:23.195
[Russ] Yeah, sign up. It's fun.
Come on down. Good times for everybody.

48:23.278 --> 48:25.155
-[Kris] No, it's not.
-[Russ] Yes, it is!

48:25.239 --> 48:29.201
[mud gurgling]

48:29.284 --> 48:32.287
[♪ tense music playing]

48:33.956 --> 48:36.834
-[wind blowing]
-[birds cawing]

48:36.917 --> 48:39.962
[Russ] You know, what I really enjoy
is making my little movies.

48:42.047 --> 48:44.508
So, in a way,
I'm a little filmmaker as well.

48:44.591 --> 48:45.843
[♪ dramatic crescendo]

48:45.926 --> 48:48.929
[projector whirring]

48:55.561 --> 49:00.691
[Carol] He works on those videos,
it seems like 24/7.

49:00.774 --> 49:04.736
And so, I constantly hear
screaming all night long.

49:04.820 --> 49:05.946
[screaming]

49:06.029 --> 49:07.155
[inaudible]

49:07.239 --> 49:10.158
[Russ] People tell me this is fake.
Is this fake right now?

49:10.242 --> 49:13.453
-[participant] No, sir, it's not fake.
-[distorted yell]

49:13.537 --> 49:16.331
[Russ] If you ever question
if we're real or not,

49:16.415 --> 49:18.750
just watch the movies

49:18.834 --> 49:20.878
and watch how these people end up.

49:20.961 --> 49:23.172
[on TV] I quit! I quit! I quit! I quit!

49:23.255 --> 49:24.298
[muffled yelling]

49:24.381 --> 49:27.926
[Russ] You'll see individuals
literally in shock.

49:28.010 --> 49:30.512
[on TV] I can't do it,
I can't do it, I can't do it. [gasps]

49:30.596 --> 49:32.848
[Russ] You'll see them
mumbling to themselves,

49:32.931 --> 49:36.143
not knowing what date it is,
not knowing who the president is.

49:36.226 --> 49:38.979
[Russ] [on TV] Who's our first president?
Quick, hurry up.

49:39.062 --> 49:41.273
-I don't know!
-[♪ dramatic crescendo]

49:42.399 --> 49:45.944
That camera. When that camera's in front,
your limits are gone.

49:46.028 --> 49:48.155
-[Russ] Put your head down.
-[Kris] Anything that you sign,

49:48.238 --> 49:49.990
thinkin' that you were getting into

49:50.073 --> 49:52.826
and those were the rules
that were set in place,

49:52.910 --> 49:56.872
they don't exist.
He wants that Kodak moment.

49:56.955 --> 50:01.168
He wants to be able to see that true fear,
when that person thinks,

50:01.251 --> 50:04.087
"I'm gonna be the first person
to die at McKamey Manor."

50:12.137 --> 50:13.764
So,

50:13.847 --> 50:15.432
it was a person,

50:15.516 --> 50:18.519
they sent me photos I hadn't seen.

50:18.602 --> 50:19.811
♪♪

50:19.895 --> 50:22.689
And it was the photos of Lori.

50:22.773 --> 50:24.775
[♪ dramatic music playing]

50:26.860 --> 50:30.822
I'm seein' this girl that was just beaten,
like a gang initiation.

50:30.906 --> 50:33.617
[clock ticking]

50:33.700 --> 50:36.578
And that's when I said,
"Why did you let that go?"

50:37.996 --> 50:39.248
And the answer I got was,

50:39.331 --> 50:42.292
"You'd be surprised what you would do
to get the right shot."

50:42.376 --> 50:44.211
[♪ dramatic sting]

50:44.294 --> 50:47.881
When I saw these pictures of Lori,
I-I couldn't do it anymore.

50:47.965 --> 50:48.966
[♪ dramatic sting]

50:49.883 --> 50:50.884
[♪ dramatic sting]

50:51.844 --> 50:52.845
[♪ dramatic sting]

50:53.804 --> 50:56.765
[♪ dramatic crescendo]

51:00.018 --> 51:02.229
-[Russ] [on TV] No?
-[Gabi] [on TV] I hate it.

51:03.063 --> 51:04.898
[Russ]
You hate it? Well,

51:04.982 --> 51:07.317
-hold still, my dear.
-No!

51:08.861 --> 51:10.153
[haunters gasp]

51:11.238 --> 51:13.740
[haunter]
Oh... God.

51:13.824 --> 51:16.618
-And just for safe--
-[Gabi whimpers]

51:16.702 --> 51:19.121
[on TV] Don't cry, you're still beautiful.

51:21.248 --> 51:24.042
Gosh. I had no idea what
I was getting myself into.

51:26.962 --> 51:29.173
I don't know how
he's able to legally do this

51:29.256 --> 51:31.175
because I don't feel like it's legal.

51:35.596 --> 51:38.640
Yeah, absolutely. I--
Whenever he's physically abusing

51:38.724 --> 51:40.934
the females who he entraps in his house.

51:41.018 --> 51:42.477
How far can we take it?

51:42.561 --> 51:44.479
I don't think I could legally sue him.

51:44.563 --> 51:47.024
We signed agreements.
We're consenting adults.

51:54.823 --> 51:57.075
I don't think there was ever a time
where I was like, I don't--

51:57.159 --> 51:59.203
Maybe the spider. But,

51:59.286 --> 52:01.663
I don't think I made it clear
with anything else

52:01.747 --> 52:03.498
that I was, like, not consenting.

52:03.582 --> 52:05.626
I didn't really feel like I
could say that, though,

52:05.709 --> 52:07.044
'cause I signed the waiver.

52:07.127 --> 52:10.631
So I think signing the waiver, I just felt
like, I was obligated to stay in it.

52:11.173 --> 52:12.883
[♪ eerie sting]

52:12.966 --> 52:15.344
We all agreed to it.

52:15.928 --> 52:17.930
[♪ eerie sting]

52:19.223 --> 52:22.434
[inaudible]

52:29.441 --> 52:31.568
There may be an element of shame

52:31.652 --> 52:34.947
in the fact that you signed up
for this experience, um,

52:35.030 --> 52:37.741
and this sense that you kind of
brought it on yourself.

52:37.824 --> 52:41.453
But, under the law, even if
they have signed a waiver,

52:42.621 --> 52:46.124
they may still have recourse
for what was done to them.

52:46.208 --> 52:49.169
[♪ soft music playing]

52:49.253 --> 52:51.213
We tend to be pretty liberal
in the United States

52:51.296 --> 52:52.923
about what you can consent to.

52:55.217 --> 52:57.886
It is certainly possible when you attend,
for example,

52:57.970 --> 53:01.265
a haunted house,
to consent to certain acts

53:01.348 --> 53:05.185
that may cause fear
or that may even touch you

53:05.269 --> 53:09.189
in what would otherwise be considered
offensive contact or battery.

53:09.273 --> 53:12.568
[overlapping screaming]

53:12.651 --> 53:16.572
But, the line is drawn
when something constitutes

53:16.655 --> 53:18.073
serious bodily injury.

53:18.156 --> 53:20.534
Examples of that would be

53:20.617 --> 53:22.369
traumatic brain injuries,

53:22.452 --> 53:23.954
fractures,

53:24.037 --> 53:25.372
back injuries,

53:25.455 --> 53:29.042
and psychological injuries
that require prolonged treatment.

53:29.126 --> 53:34.214
So, it is simply not possible
for someone to say,

53:34.298 --> 53:38.760
"Yes, I am okay with permanent physical
or psychological damage.

53:38.844 --> 53:39.928
♪♪

53:40.012 --> 53:42.014
Even if they say that,

53:42.097 --> 53:45.100
under the law, that cannot be valid.

53:45.726 --> 53:49.563
But, the other aspect of it
is that it's a violation of your consent.

53:49.646 --> 53:52.149
If, for example, your mouth is covered,

53:52.232 --> 53:53.859
so you cannot say the safe word,

53:53.942 --> 53:56.695
or the circumstances in that situation

53:56.778 --> 54:00.115
are such that you really
couldn't reasonably be expected

54:00.199 --> 54:02.659
to remember or be able
to say a safe word,

54:02.743 --> 54:07.164
but are acting in other ways that make it
very clear that you've withdrawn consent.

54:07.247 --> 54:10.083
[participant] Please, sir,
I don't wanna do this anymore, sir!

54:10.167 --> 54:12.794
Then, I think the proprietor
may have a real problem.

54:12.878 --> 54:15.881
[♪ dramatic music building]

54:19.259 --> 54:20.928
[buzzing, zap]

54:25.641 --> 54:28.352
I would love to see
the manor just go away.

54:28.894 --> 54:31.897
[Gabi] I would love to sit down
with everybody that's done it

54:31.980 --> 54:34.775
and just kind of band together and
figure out how we can make change

54:34.858 --> 54:36.318
and, like, stop him.

54:36.401 --> 54:39.071
And even if jail isn't where
he ends up, that's fine.

54:39.154 --> 54:41.323
Like, he just shouldn't
be doing what he's doing.

54:41.406 --> 54:42.574
[buzzing]

54:42.658 --> 54:46.328
[Kris] Once the fans are able
to see Russ in his true form,

54:47.913 --> 54:49.540
I'm hoping the following's gone.

54:49.623 --> 54:52.167
And when the following's gone,
the manor's gone.

54:52.251 --> 54:55.254
-[♪ tense music playing]
-[Brandon] The way that you stop him

54:56.046 --> 54:59.967
is to make sure the truth
is actually known.

55:06.431 --> 55:08.100
[speaker 7]
I wanted to do something.

55:08.183 --> 55:09.893
But I didn't know what kind of trouble

55:09.977 --> 55:12.855
I was gonna get into
from getting into somebody's emails.

55:18.068 --> 55:19.444
[speaker 7]
Definitely.

55:24.366 --> 55:26.159
It's gonna be worth it in the end.

55:30.163 --> 55:32.833
One day, I was bored.
I was looking up on the internet,

55:32.916 --> 55:36.170
"Haunted houses that pay you
for going through them."

55:36.253 --> 55:38.964
And I seen this haunted house
will give you $20,000

55:39.047 --> 55:40.924
if you make it through it.

55:41.008 --> 55:43.051
I just got married, I had an apartment,

55:43.135 --> 55:45.929
and, um, I was like, "Man,
$20,000 is a lot of money."

55:46.013 --> 55:48.182
So, I could use that, and there's no way

55:48.265 --> 55:49.933
I was not gonna get that $20,000.

55:50.017 --> 55:52.227
-His hands are shaking.
-[haunter] Oh, I know.

55:52.311 --> 55:53.520
-He is shaking, isn't he?
-[haunter] Oh, yeah.

55:53.604 --> 55:56.607
-[haunter] Pop 'em one, Russ.
-[mumbling, grunts]

55:57.524 --> 56:00.027
[Russ]
Come on. Follow my voice, let's go.

56:00.110 --> 56:03.989
-[Justin groaning, panting]
-[rattling]

56:04.072 --> 56:07.117
-I'm suggesting you quit.
-[Justin] Never.

56:07.201 --> 56:10.954
-[Russ] Never. Never? He says never!
-I was arguing with him back.

56:11.038 --> 56:13.749
Like, I wasn't bein' passive.
I wasn't bein' submissive to him.

56:13.832 --> 56:15.417
And I think that's what
really got him mad.

56:15.501 --> 56:18.253
-Sleep first, then you can do it.
-For the easiest--

56:18.337 --> 56:20.380
I don't fall for that crap. Just sleep.

56:20.464 --> 56:24.051
-Okay, y-you need to be quiet.
-No, I don't, dude. What a joke--

56:24.134 --> 56:26.303
-[Russ] You want a joke, huh?
-[indistinct]

56:26.386 --> 56:28.931
-You know what? You're done.
-[Justin] Don't even do it, dude. No.

56:29.014 --> 56:30.933
-Get the hell off me.
-[Russ] Keep that camera on.

56:31.016 --> 56:34.895
This is what we're seeing right now.
You're out of it right now. You're done.

56:34.978 --> 56:37.147
[Justin]
I thought there was gonna be $20,000.

56:37.231 --> 56:40.150
I thought there was gonna be a haunt.
I wasted all my money

56:40.234 --> 56:42.819
and my work days and all that
going there, just to get humiliated.

56:42.903 --> 56:44.947
What a freak show that was, right?

56:45.030 --> 56:46.823
At that point I wasn't even mad
about the money anymore,

56:46.907 --> 56:47.908
it was just the embarrassment.

56:47.991 --> 56:49.993
[♪ rhythmic dramatic music playing]

56:52.663 --> 56:55.958
So, I started a Facebook page called,
"McKamey Manor Exposed."

56:56.041 --> 56:59.002
[♪ synth music playing]

56:59.086 --> 57:01.630
I wanted it to be a place
where people could actually come,

57:01.713 --> 57:04.883
say what they need to say
without having to worry about threats.

57:10.138 --> 57:13.892
The biggest thing we found, though,
was we actually got into Russ's emails.

57:13.976 --> 57:15.978
[mouse scrolling]

57:16.061 --> 57:19.565
Russ has a very old email service,
and that's where he messed up.

57:20.190 --> 57:23.110
The company that Russ has for the email
has a phone number.

57:23.193 --> 57:26.113
So, I called them, and I was like,
"Hey, yeah, I my password."

57:26.864 --> 57:30.158
So, they says, "Okay, what's your name?"
"Russ McKamey."

57:30.242 --> 57:32.870
He's like, "Okay, when's the last time
you were on your email?"

57:32.953 --> 57:34.663
And I was like, you know,
I'm gonna make a good guess.

57:34.746 --> 57:35.873
I'll say, "Oh it was yesterday."

57:35.956 --> 57:37.499
She's like, "Oh, alright.
Yeah, that was correct."

57:37.583 --> 57:39.793
I changed the password
for my email address,

57:39.877 --> 57:42.629
and then I locked him out.
We hit the jackpot.

57:42.713 --> 57:45.799
[♪ dramatic music playing]

57:48.427 --> 57:52.181
From his email, we found that
he wasn't paying his taxes on his barn.

57:53.724 --> 57:56.310
And Russ wrote this email
back to the tax guy saying,

57:56.393 --> 57:58.979
"This manor is fake.
Everything I'm saying is fake."

57:59.062 --> 58:02.691
"Russ, I talked to my lawyer today."
I got Russ here with his tax problems.

58:02.774 --> 58:06.278
This is from Russ's son:
"You absolutely disgust me."

58:06.361 --> 58:09.489
[typing]

58:09.573 --> 58:13.368
This guy's really obsessed and, like,
really going after his girlfriend.

58:13.452 --> 58:15.954
"What you did was
absolutely unacceptable."

58:16.038 --> 58:18.999
So I took those emails,
I took screenshots, and I showed those.

58:19.082 --> 58:21.376
Here's the proof right here.
This is, like, something

58:21.460 --> 58:25.255
you're never gonna see anywhere else.
I put everything on my Facebook page,

58:25.339 --> 58:27.466
And I was like,
"You guys gotta tell your stories."

58:27.549 --> 58:30.552
-[typing]
-[♪ dramatic crescendo]

58:31.261 --> 58:32.930
All these other groups popped up.

58:33.013 --> 58:35.015
♪♪

58:35.098 --> 58:37.684
[Kris]
People started posting stuff online

58:37.768 --> 58:40.145
that Russ definitely
didn't want anybody to see.

58:40.604 --> 58:44.441
-Guys, he will stuff you in a freezer
full of water upside down until you tap.

58:44.525 --> 58:48.195
[victim] [over phone]
He got his claws so onto my brain.

58:48.654 --> 58:51.740
Once I got away from it, I was like,
I'm just gonna expose him.

58:51.823 --> 58:54.201
This is where
he's reading over the waiver.

58:54.284 --> 58:55.619
[video chatter]

58:55.702 --> 58:57.996
So, I posted the reaction videos
on YouTube.

58:58.080 --> 59:00.415
I was very surprised at
how many people saw it.

59:00.499 --> 59:04.962
I was in water, and I had, like,
this much air to breathe.

59:05.045 --> 59:08.257
Fast forward to now, it's, like,
two-point-something million views.

59:08.340 --> 59:12.469
[Brandon] There's so much drama
in these online communities, right?

59:12.553 --> 59:15.806
It's the McKamey Manor
Facebook group people

59:15.889 --> 59:16.890
fighting these people,

59:16.974 --> 59:18.767
and then those people are
fighting against these people.

59:18.851 --> 59:22.354
[overlapping swearing, yelling]

59:22.437 --> 59:24.481
[Justin]
If you go on his Facebook page,

59:24.565 --> 59:26.191
it's a straight-up cult.

59:26.275 --> 59:28.527
They are obsessed with him.
Like, they don't care.

59:28.610 --> 59:32.072
Russ could say the sky is green,
and they'll say, "Yes, sir, it is green."

59:33.323 --> 59:35.826
They will go after the people

59:35.909 --> 59:38.245
who they perceive as one of their enemies

59:38.328 --> 59:41.039
or one of their haters
with everything that they have.

59:41.123 --> 59:43.458
[♪ dramatic music playing]

59:43.542 --> 59:45.627
[Gabi]
He would send people to the haters.

59:45.711 --> 59:49.089
He called everyone a hater
that didn't agree with what he was doing,

59:49.173 --> 59:52.885
and he basically encouraged them to, like,
bully, destroy someone on the internet.

59:53.802 --> 59:56.972
I just got jumped on by all these people
from Russ or whatever,

59:57.055 --> 59:58.807
and they just tore me apart.

59:59.308 --> 01:00:02.269
One guy text me a picture
of where I work at.

01:00:02.352 --> 01:00:04.229
"You're gonna get a call from us," and,

01:00:04.313 --> 01:00:06.815
you know, "See your online activities
of what you're doin'."

01:00:06.899 --> 01:00:09.193
It's not Russ doin' this.
It's his followers.

01:00:09.276 --> 01:00:12.863
People started showing
personal pictures of me on the internet.

01:00:12.946 --> 01:00:16.533
Then went to phone numbers,
then went to addresses.

01:00:16.617 --> 01:00:20.454
I would get anonymous emails
that were saying some godawful things.

01:00:20.537 --> 01:00:23.373
